AB  - Since the 1960s experimental artists have invested live performance with the promise of truth, nonconformism, and progressive change. The resulting discourse of liveness salvaged some performance from centuries of antitheatrical prejudice while perpetuating the prejudice against theatre. Bloody Mess (2004), by Forced Entertainment, urges a reconsideration of this discourse at the turn of the century when new reality TV formats challenged the association of liveness with progressivism. Taking a historical approach to the performative production of the real, the show helps us see how television, by becoming the new target of the cultural anxieties once associated with theatre, enabled non-televised live performance to emerge as a medium of truth in the 1960s.
